Tracking America's recovery

From your job to your home to your groceries, Covid-19 has disrupted nearly every aspect of life. This dashboard shows how the economy continues to change as we grapple with life during the pandemic.

Check back regularly to see how America is recovering and adapting to a new normal.

The Back-to-Normal Index

The pandemic economy is far from normal. So Moody’s Analytics and CNN Business have partnered to create a proprietary Back-to-Normal Index, comprised of 37 national and seven state-level indicators. The index ranges from zero, representing no economic activity, to 100%, representing the economy returning to its pre-pandemic level in March 2020.
United States

95%

The economy in the United States is operating at 95% of where it was in early March.

Your Job

Unemployment claims

Continued claims, which track Americans filing for jobless benefits for at least two weeks in a row, peaked above 23 million in the spring of 2020. Click above to see initial jobless claims.

Note: Not seasonally adjusted
Source: US Dept. of Labor via FRED Data as of October 14, 2021

State unemployment rates

Nationally, the unemployment rate hit a pandemic-era high of 14.8% in April 2020. Click the map to see the unemployment rate in your state.

Unemployment Rate
Less than 5.0%
5.1% to 7.0%
7.1% to 9.0%
9.1% to 11.0%
11.1% or more
Note: Seasonally adjusted
Source: US Bureau of Labor Statistics via FRED Data as of September 20, 2021

Getting hired

Early in the pandemic, LinkedIn noticed a dramatic decline in the number of their users updating their job information, compared to a year ago — a sign that hiring had ground to a halt.

Note: Data is calculated on a 14-day rolling basis and is based on the number of LinkedIn users who added a new employer to their profile during this period, compared to the same period in 2019
Source: LinkedIn Data as of October 19, 2021

Layoffs and quits

Layoffs surged in March 2020 but have since fallen back to pre-recession levels. The quit rate is also at pre-recession levels.

Layoffs

Quits

Note: Seasonally adjusted
Source: US Bureau of Labor Statistics via FRED Data as of October 12, 2021

Job postings

Early in the pandemic, LinkedIn noticed a huge decline in new job postings. Click the dropdown menu to see how job listings have changed since February 2020 in each industry.

Note: 14-day average indexed to the week ending February 12, 2020, based on the number of job postings on LinkedIn during this period
Source: Linkedin Data as of October 19, 2021

Your Home

30-year mortgage rate

It's one of the cheapest times in history to take out a mortgage. But low rates can only boost the housing market so much. Getting a mortgage during the pandemic is a little different, with lenders looking more carefully at borrowers.

Note: 30-year fixed rate mortage average
Source: Freddie Mac via FRED Data as of October 14, 2021

Your Investments

Dow Jones Industrial Average

At the start of the pandemic, the Dow fell 34% between its all-time high on February 19 and March 23. It then staged a full recovery, surging to record highs.

35,609.34152.030.43%
Source: CNN Business Data as of October 21, 2021

Your Money

Personal savings

The personal savings rate measures the portion of income that Americans don't spend or pay out in taxes. The jump in April 2020 reflects when the government first sent stimulus checks to households.

Source: US Bureau of Economic Analysis via FRED Data as of October 01, 2021

Consumer credit

Americans are spending far less on their credit cards than they did before the pandemic.

Note: Consumer Loans: Credit Cards and Other Revolving Plans, Seasonally adjusted
Source: Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System via FRED Data as of October 15, 2021

Your Spending

Small business closures

Across the country, many small businesses have closed either temporarily or permanently because they've been hit hard by the pandemic.

Percent of small businesses closed
Less than 0%

Note: Compared to median number of businesses open on same weekdays in January 2020
Source: Homebase Data as of October 20, 2021

E-commerce spending

Consumers shifted from brick-and-mortar stores to online retailers during the pandemic. E-commerce spending, as tracked by Adobe, is significantly higher than before the pandemic.
